{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15003"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15003"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0,0.27,0.36,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66742"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52196"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66742"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory techniques are essential for detecting and analysing proteins in biological samples.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory techniques involves separating proteins by molecular weight and detecting the presence of specific proteins using antibodies?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flow cytometry analysis","Polymerase chain reaction","Western blotting","Serum protein electrophoresis","Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EWestern blotting\u003C/strong\u003E, which combines protein separation by molecular weight using sodium dodecyl sulphate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE) with specific protein detection using labelled antibodies. The proteins are first separated on a gel, transferred to a membrane, then probed with specific antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect techniques can be distinguished as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlow cytometry analysis\u003C/strong\u003E analyses intact cells based on their size, granularity and fluorescent markers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymerase chain reaction\u003C/strong\u003E amplifies DNA sequences and is not used for protein detection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E separates proteins based on their electrical charge but does not use specific antibody detection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzyme-linked immunosorbent assay\u003C/strong\u003E detects proteins using antibodies but does not separate them by size first\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWestern blotting is particularly useful when both the molecular weight and identity of a protein need to be determined.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Western blotting separates proteins by molecular weight using gel electrophoresis followed by transfer to a membrane for antibody detection","Western blotting is distinct from other protein detection methods as it provides both size information and specific protein identification","The technique involves three key steps: separation by size, transfer to membrane, and antibody-based detection"],"references":["Hnasko TS, Hnasko RM. The Western Blot. Methods Mol Biol. 2015;1318:87-96. doi: 10.1007/978-1-4939-2742-5_9. PMID: 26160567.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52196"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15003"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52196"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:44:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:47:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66742"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4908"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Immunology","synon